                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00 Bandit Activities, 1931/237:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Beaulac</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-17T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 17, 1931—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>175. American Consul, Bluefields, telegraphed September 11<note n="51"
                        xml:id="d945fn51">Telegram not printed.</note> he has informed you of
                    reported death sentences imposed on two bandits following court martial by
                    Guardia. See Department’s January 16, 1930, 6 p.m., January 17, 1930, 5 p.m. and
                    January 29, 4 p.m., and <pb facs="0990" n="870" xml:id="pg_870"/> endeavor to
                    see to it that death sentences if imposed are not carried out.</p>
                <p>Advise what action subsequent to Legation’s No. 1328, February 18, 1930, has been
                    taken by Nicaraguan Government to establish civil courts adequate to deal with
                    cases involving banditry.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
